title: For Sale:  S&W Model 49-2
postcontent:
This S&W Model 49 Bodyguard has a steel frame, 2 inch barrel and was discontinued in 1996.  Five shot, double action/single action with a bobbed hammer.  This pistol was actualy made to be fired from inside a coat pocket.  The same pistol made famous in the 1968 Pulitzer Prize winning photo.  

This pistol came out of an estate.  When I found it, it was wrapped in duct tape and inside some foam padding.  The duct tape ate through the blue into the metal.  I completely disassembled the pistol, sandblasted it down to bare metal, and coated it with Dura Coat flat black.  There is still sign of the damage to the metal visible under the coating.  It also now has a fine cylinder line from turning while shooting.  I replaced the grips with a nice pair of S&W logo grips.  Fun to shoot, without much recoil, but plenty of noise.  I'll include a partial box of ammo if you don't make a stupid offer.

This would make a nice CCW or back up piece.  FTF in Colorado Springs with cash, and a bill of sale will be exchanged with proper ID.  Not interested in trades.

Functionally 100%

Cosmetically amazing, I would put it at 90% or better.

The Cass County Historical Society, Inc. will celebrate the rich cultural heritage of its people by connecting them with their past, present, and future.

The Cass County Historical Society, Inc. was organized in 1965 for the purpose of discovering, collecting and preserving material which identifies and illustrates the history of this area. We collect material illustrative of life conditions, events and activities of the past and present. The society has published books dealing with family histories, a history of Harrisonville, cemetery guides, calendars, and reprinted plat books.

The society provides for the preservation of such material and makes it accessible to the public in the Margaret Wade Archives, located in the Cass County Information Center at 400 E. Mechanic. There it houses many county records such as probate packets, deed books and indices, court records, marriage records, tax records, etc. Volunteers have prepared indices for birth and death records, census and marriage records, and over 60,000 obituaries to name a few.
